PREREQUISITES
-------------
  - Go 1.26+
  - Linux with IOMMU/VFIO enabled
  - Vivado 2023.2 (for synthesis)

  VFIO needs IOMMU enabled in BIOS and in the kernel parameters
  (intel_iommu=on or amd_iommu=on).


HOW IT WORKS
------------
  scan  ->  check  ->  build  ->  flash

  scan     enumerate PCI devices, detect VFIO status
  check    validate the donor device, read config space and BARs
  build    clone identity -> generate SV/COE/TCL -> Vivado synthesis -> .bin
  flash    write the bitstream to the FPGA board

The donor device is read through VFIO; its config space, BARs and
capabilities are cloned, scrubbed, and compiled into ready-to-flash
firmware. Run the stages in order.


QUICK START
-----------
  git clone --recurse-submodules https://github.com/sercanarga/PCILeechGen.git
  cd PCILeechGen && make build

  sudo ./bin/pcileechgen scan
  sudo ./bin/pcileechgen check --bdf 0000:02:00.0
  sudo ./bin/pcileechgen build --bdf 0000:02:00.0 --board CaptainDMA_100T

  Run "check" before "build" to verify donor and board compatibility.
  Full synthesis takes 30-60 minutes; add --skip-vivado for artifacts only.


COMMANDS
--------
  scan             list PCI devices with VFIO status
  check            validate a donor device (BAR size vs board BRAM)
  build            generate firmware artifacts (+ Vivado)
  validate         verify artifacts match the donor context (--force for truncated)
  mmio-trace       capture live or import saved BAR MMIO access traces
  boards           list supported FPGA boards
  version          print version

  Common build flags:
    --bdf <addr>       donor device BDF (required)
    --board <name>     target board (required)
    --skip-vivado      artifacts only, no synthesis
    --force            allow donor BAR > board BRAM (may truncate)
    --from-json <f>    offline build from saved device_context.json
    --mmio-trace <f>   saved MMIO trace JSON (mmio-trace --output) for
                       measured TLP latency instead of synthetic defaults
    --output <dir>     output directory (default: pcileech_datastore)
    --emulate-pm       keep donor PM capability faithful (cosmetic D-state;
                       IP core stays D0 for DMA stability)
    --no-vfio          sysfs-only donor capture, no vfio-pci bind (for hosts
                       without IOMMU/VFIO or when donor can't be unbound)
    --option-rom       capture + serve the donor expansion ROM via BAR6
    --ila              insert a Vivado ILA debug core (probes BAR/TLP/interrupt)
    --ila-depth <n>    ILA capture depth in samples (default 1024)
    --probe-bars       write-probe BAR registers (default on; auto-skipped for
                       network cards; set --probe-bars=false if a donor hangs)
    --fallback-config <f>  custom fallback defaults YAML (fills zeroed BAR
                       registers by device class; empty = built-in defaults)
    --stock-bar        diagnostic: use stock bar controller (skip custom SV)
    --vivado-path <p>  path to Vivado installation
    --jobs <n>         parallel Vivado jobs (default 4)
    --timeout <s>      Vivado synthesis timeout in seconds (default 3600)

  Global flags (all commands):
    --log-level <lvl>  debug|info|warn|error (default info)
    --log-file <f>     tee the full pre/mid/post-generation run to a file
    --json-logs        structured JSON logs

  Offline MMIO trace import:
    pcileechgen mmio-trace --trace-file mmiotrace.txt --bar-base 0xf7800000 \
      --bar-index 2 --bar-size 4096 --class-code 0x010802 --json


FEATURES
--------
  Device identity
    - VID/DID/REV, subsystem IDs, class code
    - Device Serial Number (stripped when the donor has none)

  BAR emulation
    - dynamic BAR0 sizing from the donor (capped by board bram_size)
    - 64-bit BAR preservation, power-of-2 rounding
    - MSI-X table placement that avoids NVMe doorbell overlap
    - donor-faithful MSI-X offset (table sits where the donor's does)
    - generic BRAM BAR fallback seeded from the donor snapshot
    - option ROM serving via BAR6 (--option-rom)
    - multi-BAR support: BAR3-6 real aperture where the donor has them

  Device classes (modeled register-level behavior)
    - NVMe: CC.EN -> CSTS.RDY handshake, admin queue responder (Identify,
      Get/Set Features, Create IO CQ/SQ, Get Log Page), DMA bridge, IO
      backing store (BRAM sector cache for read/write round-trip)
    - xHCI: Command Ring + Event Ring engine (No-Op, Enable Slot, completion
      events), interrupt via IMAN.IP
    - Audio (HDA): RIRB DMA bridge, codec response injection, MSI interrupt
    - SATA/AHCI: donor ATA IDENTIFY block generation (sim-only, not yet
      integrated into codegen)
    - Ethernet, GPU, WiFi, Thunderbolt, RAID, SDHCI: class-aware fallback
      defaults and BAR models

  Config space
    - 4KB shadow + 17-pass scrubbing pipeline
    - per-register write masks, per-bit W1C masks (pcileech_cfgspace_w1cmask.coe)
    - capability filtering/pruning (bodies fully zeroed, not just headers)
    - PCIe cap injection, power-management lock, vendor quirks
    - spec-accurate read-only locking (write-to-RO-then-readback detection)
    - AER mask/severity preserved from donor (not overwritten with spec defaults)

  Stealth and timing
    - TLP latency emulation (xorshift128+ CDF reproduction)
    - write-completion emulation, completion timeout
    - ASPM clamping, DSN jitter, per-build placement randomization
    - VSEC entropy embed
    - PM emulation (--emulate-pm: cosmetic D-state, IP core stays D0)

  Diagnostics
    - VFIO diagnostics, BAR vs BRAM compatibility checks
    - post-build validation (validate --board --force), build manifest,
      config-space diff report
    - Code-10 risk report (code10_report.txt): BAR truncation, FSM gaps,
      interrupt routing, MSI-X relocation, missing DSN
    - detectability audit: severity-rated residual enumeration tells
      (check --board <name>) - flags link mismatch, stripped caps, etc.
    - ILA debug core (--ila): JTAG capture of BAR/TLP/interrupt signals
    - iverilog sim harness (make sim): cfg_w1c_shadow, msix_pba, nvme_store,
      ahci_engine, xhci_ring_engine

SUPPORTED BOARDS
----------------
  Board             FPGA           Lanes  Form factor
  --------------    -----------    -----  -----------
  CaptainDMA_M2_x1  XC7A35T-325    x1     M.2
  CaptainDMA_M2_x4  XC7A35T-325    x4     M.2
  CaptainDMA_35T    XC7A35T-484    x1     PCIe
  CaptainDMA_75T    XC7A75T-484    x1     PCIe
  CaptainDMA_100T   XC7A100T-484   x1     PCIe
  ScreamerM2        XC7A35T-325    x1     M.2
  pciescreamer      XC7A35T-484    x1     PCIe
  NeTV2_35T         XC7A35T-484    x1     M.2
  NeTV2_100T        XC7A100T-484   x1     M.2
  PCIeSquirrel      XC7A35T-484    x1     PCIe
  EnigmaX1          XC7A75T-484    x1     PCIe
  ZDMA              XC7A100T-484   x4     PCIe
  GBOX              XC7A35T-484    x1     Mini PCIe
  ac701_ft601       XC7A200T-676   x4     Dev Board
  acorn             XC7A200T-484   x4     M.2
  litefury          XC7A100T-484   x4     M.2
  sp605_ft601       XC6SLX45T-484  x1     Dev Board

  Boards with larger bram_size (EnigmaX1=8K, CaptainDMA_75T=16K,
  CaptainDMA_100T / ZDMA / NeTV2_100T / ac701_ft601 / acorn / litefury=32K)
  support larger BAR0 emulation. Run "boards" for the full list.


OUTPUT
------
  pcileech_datastore/
    device_context.json                 donor snapshot (includes build entropy)
    pcileech_cfgspace.coe               4KB scrubbed config space
    pcileech_cfgspace_writemask.coe     per-register write masks
    pcileech_cfgspace_w1cmask.coe       per-bit write-1-to-clear mask
    pcileech_bar_zero4k.coe             BAR0 content (sized to donor/BRAM)
    bar_behavior_profile.json           BAR probing results (RW/W1C bits)
    pcileech_bar_impl_device.sv         register-level BAR implementation
    pcileech_bar_impl_msi.sv            MSI interrupt controller (if MSI)
    pcileech_tlps128_bar_controller.sv  TLP BAR controller
    pcileech_msix_table.sv              MSI-X table + PBA (if MSI-X)
    pcileech_nvme_admin_responder.sv    NVMe admin responder (if NVMe)
    pcileech_nvme_dma_bridge.sv         NVMe DMA bridge (if NVMe)
    pcileech_hda_msi.sv                 HDA MSI interrupt gen (if Audio)
    pcileech_hda_rirb_dma.sv            HDA RIRB DMA bridge (if Audio)
    tlp_latency_emulator.sv             response latency emulation
    device_config.sv                    identity + feature flags
    config_space_init.hex               config space init ($readmemh)
    msix_table_init.hex                 MSI-X table init ($readmemh)
    identify_init.hex                   NVMe Identify ROM (if NVMe)
    bar_init.hex                        generic BRAM BAR init (if generic class)
    vivado_generate_project.tcl         project creation
    vivado_build.tcl                    synthesis script
    code10_report.txt                   Code-10 risk summary for this build
    ila_debug.txt                       ILA JTAG capture workflow (if --ila)
    scrub_diff_report.txt               config space scrubbing diff
    build_manifest.json                 checksums + metadata
    src/                                patched board SV sources
    *.bin                               bitstream (after Vivado)


DEVELOPMENT
-----------
  make build          build the binary
  make test           run all tests (with -race)
  make test-coverage  tests with coverage report
  make lint           run linter (golangci-lint)
  make check          vet + lint + test
  make sim            unit-simulate the behavioral RTL modules (needs iverilog)
  make hdl-lint       lint generated SV with verilator
  make fixtures       generate synthetic donor fixture JSONs
  make install        install binary to GOPATH/bin
  make fmt            format code
  make vet            vet code
  make clean          clean build artifacts


UTILITIES
---------
Windows device-history cleanup

  After flashing and testing, Windows caches device metadata in the
  registry. Stale entries from earlier builds can cause conflicts, Code 10
  errors, or driver misidentification. The tools/ directory has an
  interactive cleanup utility:

    cleanup_device_history.bat      double-click launcher (runs as Admin)
    cleanup_device_history.ps1      PowerShell script with arrow-key menu

  Usage:
    double-click cleanup_device_history.bat and confirm the UAC prompt, or
    open PowerShell as Administrator and run: .\cleanup_device_history.ps1

  Features:
    - scans PCI and USB device history across all ControlSets
    - deduplicates by hardware ID and instance ID
    - interactive arrow-key menu with driver info and type tags
    - automatic registry backup to the desktop before any change
    - cleans setupapi logs, DeviceMetadataStore, PnP event logs

  Requires Administrator privileges. Reboot after cleanup before reconnecting
  the device.


